
** Installation

  - *GNU_SECURE* points to a file that contains the host that are
    allowed to connect to the local emacs. E.g. ~/.gnuserv. Under W2K
    the *GNU_SECURE* environment is ignored.

    <example>
    localhost
    </example>

  - (require '*gnuserv*) on W2K
  - (require '*gnuserv-compat*) on GNU/Linux

  - (gnuserv-start) ;; see also local/elisp/auto/gnuserv.el

** Files

  - gnuserv
  - gnuclient
  - gnudoit
  - .gnuserv (*GNU_SECURE*)
  - gnuserv.el
  - gnuserv-compat.el

** Test whether a emacs is running

  - The following script returns t if emacs is running otherwise it
    returns an empty string.

    <example>
    $ gnuclient -batch -eval t 2>/dev/null
    </example>
